### What it is (the breakthrough itself)
Normally, when two photons are entangled via spontaneous parametric down-conversion (SPDC), they share fixed properties like orbital angular momentum (OAM), denoted \(\ell\) (in units of \(\hbar\)). Self-torque, discovered classically in 2019, is when a light pulse’s OAM **changes continuously over its own duration**—the “twist” ramps up or down in time, like a screw tightening as the pulse travels.

**QSTEP** is the first quantum version: a pair of entangled photons where **each photon’s OAM varies over time in a perfectly correlated way**. The pump laser imprints a time-dependent OAM ramp, and conservation of angular momentum during SPDC forces the signal and idler photons to inherit **correlated dynamic twists**.

Mathematically (simple form from angular-momentum conservation in the nonlinear process):
\[
\ell_{\text{pump}}(t) = \ell_{\text{signal}}(t) + \ell_{\text{idler}}(t)
\]
where \(\ell_{\text{pump}}(t) = \ell_0 + r \cdot t\) (linear ramp from the delayed-vortex pump, \(r\) = torque rate). The photons are entangled not just in a single \(\ell\) value, but across the entire **time-evolving OAM trajectory**. This adds a continuous temporal degree of freedom to the quantum Hilbert space—dramatically expanding it beyond today’s static high-dimensional OAM entanglement.

